{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 A new origin myth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The myth of Electronic Music\u8217's origin, as it was handed down to me, was always told through the perspective of the tape recorder being the unquestionable beginning of it all. Then later, the result of that historical perspective sees the tape recorder grow to the size of the studio, with it\u8217's undeniable monumental prestige. If we adjust the point of departure to a more recent technological breakthrough, then the scope of our story changes dramatically. To use the MPC as the starting point for an alternative telling of history emerges as an opportunity. If we dare to follow this line of thinking further, we arrive at taking actions in the present, in order to create the kind of future we would most prefer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The story we now construct has ramifications for where density occurs within the story. My preference is for density to occur closer to our time. Year zero is no longer the end of WWII with that of the Americans \u8220"liberating\u8221" the tape recorder from the rubble of continental Europe. Instead, the year is 1988. Public Enemy burst into a popular culture running at break-neck-speed with their debut release {\i It Takes a Nation of Millions to Hold Us Back}. In the same year N.W.A release {\i Straight Outta Compton}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Our origin story is no longer one of first meanderings of applying an alien technology inside of a void. Instead the very modus operandi is referentiality. The sampler and sampling, not the tape recorder and tape recordings of trains or doors and sighs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As stated above the history of Electronic Music begins with the tape recorder and then explodes outward into the physical monument of the studio. Our new origin story is one of implosion. From the decisively physical 10,5 Kilos of the original MPC-60 to the weightlessness of software. Both stories originate from a single machine but constitutes wildly different points of departure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I argue that sampler softwares, running inside of computers, are direct descendants of the MPC. As software they are now devoid of physical form. A computer can perform the task of any specialized machine like the tape recorder or the sampler. A general purpose computer is incorporeal. Purpose defined in software.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Over embellished symmetry\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It wasn\u8217't until much later that I realised that the \u8220"magical machine\u8221" that I had heard about was the MPC. I first heard the story when I was a kid listening to NWA, Public Enemy and De La Soul. Then finally when I was older from a friend who turned me on to J-Dilla\u8217's Donuts. He told me the story of how the record got made as we were listening to the album together. The last celebrated experimental hip hop record, and it didn\u8217't have any rapping on it. The story goes he made it in the hospital as he was dying of a terminal illness. Had his MPC3000 on his belly in the hospital bed. I don\u8217't know if that\u8217's entirely accurate. That image is so strong that I\u8217've put off trying to find out if it\u8217's a 100% true story because\par}
